Dear Gregory:

I recently inquired of John C. Wells, a linguist who lectures at 
University College in London, about the substitution of &quot;chr&quot; for &quot;tr&quot;.  
According to him, this is not a known dialect from any geographical 
region, but is, apparently, a peculiarity of some people&#39;s speech, and I 
suspect a very small percentage of English speakers do this.

Paige

Gregory Weidman wrote:
&gt;
&gt; Dear Anthony,
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;m having trouble seeing how to work a strictly phonetic approach in 
&gt; real life even within my own writing. My family and I discussed 
&gt; recently the different pronunciations of the &quot;t&quot; in &quot;train&quot; that we 
&gt; have among us. The difference is that sometimes TOT is used, and 
&gt; sometimes CHURCH is used. Listening to myself carefully in this and 
&gt; similar words, I find that most of the time I use TOT, but on occasion 
&gt; I will start this word with CHURCH. Should I write the exact same word 
&gt; differently depending on which pronunciation I use in a particular 
&gt; context? Certainly not, since I intend the same phoneme in each 
&gt; context. Writing this word phonetically just introduces confusion.
&gt;
&gt; Other consonant problems are one of emphasis. When I want to emphasize 
&gt; the word &quot;Matter,&quot; I will use TOT in the middle of it. When I am not 
&gt; emphasizing the word, I use &quot;DEAD&quot; in the middle of it. Should I spell 
&gt; the same word differently depending on whether I am emphasizing it? I 
&gt; hardly think so. (Just as a note -- I use DEAD in the middle of 
&gt; &quot;Matters&quot; almost exclusively, even when emphasizing it.) In each case, 
&gt; the same phoneme is communicated, even if they are phonetically distinct.
&gt;
&gt; There&#39;s been much discussion about vowels in this topic -- I think 
&gt; because vowels in English convey relatively less information than 
&gt; consonants do. However, adopting a phonetic approach causes countless 
&gt; painful issues in relation to consonants as well.
&gt;
&gt; As an aside, has anyone else noticed that Read uses THITHER instead of 
&gt; THOTH in the words &quot;with&quot; and &quot;without&quot; on page 11 of QM? Is this 
&gt; really the way he pronounced these words? I can&#39;t even get my mouth to 
&gt; form that sound in the middle of &quot;without.&quot; Of course, that might 
&gt; explain why he needed an abbreviation for &quot;with&quot; when WOW-IT-THOTH is 
&gt; so easy to write. I don&#39;t think this observation helps my argument at 
&gt; all, but it is an interesting point to consider as we discuss this. I 
&gt; guess I do use THITHER in the middle of &quot;within,&quot; but never in 
&gt; &quot;without.&quot; If I followed a strictly phonetic approach, I&#39;d be spelling 
&gt; these two obviously related words with different consonants and 
&gt; increasing confusion. Instead, I think they should both be constructed 
&gt; using however I spell &quot;with&quot; -- in this case WOW-IT-THOTH -- combined 
&gt; with the appropriate suffixes.
&gt;
&gt; Thanks,
&gt; Greg
