&gt; Here&#39;s my main objection in a nutshell:
&gt;
&gt; - Kingsley spells &quot;path&quot; with #32 Ah and &quot;as&quot; with #30 At
&gt;
&gt; - Most Americans spell both &quot;path&quot; and &quot;as&quot; with #30 At
&gt;
&gt; If we must all now use #32 for the word &quot;path&quot; while still using
&gt;
&gt; #30 for &quot;as&quot; it would be problem enough. But worse is that
&gt;
&gt; most Americans could never use QS correctly as they would never know
&gt;
&gt; where to put other words with the &quot;apple&quot; sound ( sampa /{/ ). One
&gt;
&gt; could try to write a Byzantine rule to help but it would never work
&gt;
&gt; because as John Cowan wrote earlier &quot;...If you can&#39;t hear the
&gt;
&gt; difference, you&#39;re going to make mistakes...&quot; . And the result of these
&gt;
&gt; inevitable errors will be more illegible than QS written in dialect
&gt;
&gt; ever would.
&gt;
&gt; Now if we let Americans use #30 for the word &quot;path&quot; then we must
&gt;
&gt; let Tasmanians use #28 if they want. I have observed that this creates
&gt;
&gt; no difficulties in practice and we will still all be able to read
&gt;
&gt; their towering body of literature without difficulty.
